NATIVES[Catchment]=0.002811
	~	$M/ha
	~	Taken from 'Retiring Farmland into Native using the Tīmata Method' Our Land Our \
		Water slides. 2022 value from 'Timata Forestry Grade 3 m spacing'.
		
		2022 establishment costs in the Bay of Plenty using this method were approximately \
		$2.20 per plant,
		which covered pre-plant spot spray, plants and planting. This equates to a cost of \
		$2,811 per ha at (3m
		spacings - 1,111 plants per ha) or $6,050 per ha at (2m spacings – 2,500 plants \
		per ha). This compares
		to a conventional large grade/high density cost of $30,222 per ha ($6.80 per plant \
		at 1.5m spacings or
		4,444 plants per ha)
	|

land loss[Intervention,Catchment]=INIPASTORALFARMLAND[Catchment]-Tot Land[Intervention\
		,Catchment]
	~	ha
	~		|

STOCK ADJUST TIME=10
	~	yr
	~	τ is Stock_Adjust_Time.
		
		Good default values (NZ sheep & beef context)
		
		3 years: fast response (hard destocking/restocking, but still not instant)
		
		5 years: solid general default (often “feels right” in regional models)
		
		10 years: slow response (conservative behaviour / strong inertia)
		
		If you want one number to start with: use 5 years.
		
		How it behaves (so you can pick confidently)
		
		A first-order stock reaches roughly:
		
		63% of the way to the new capacity after 1 × τ
		
		86% after 2 × τ
		
		95% after 3 × τ
		
		So:
		
		τ = 5 years →  95% adjustment in  15 years
		
		τ = 10 years →  95% adjustment in  30 years
	|

